<div id="review_3968073817" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3968073817" />
    <a title="nastya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24672869-nastya"><img alt="nastya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615523127p2/24672869.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3968073817?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="nastya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="nastya" href="/user/show/24672869-nastya">nastya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18930219-life-and-fate">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24672869-nastya?shelf=20th-century">20th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24672869-nastya?shelf=rus">rus</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3968073817" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17107451110685692859"><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1621889389i/31385175._SX540_.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/>There’re a lot of reviews about this book being an epic, and the 20th century answer to War and Peace. But for me it was just an incredibly engaging story, never have I felt this with Tolstoy’s work.<br/>This novel is panoramic in scope, Grossman looks very wide, tries to give us the biggest slice of life he can. <br/><br/>It is about war and about civilians trying to survive in nazi concentration camps, GULAG, in evacuation, under occupation, on the battlefront. Stakes couldn’t be higher, risks are immense. B</span>
  <span id="freeText17107451110685692859" style="display:none"><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1621889389i/31385175._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>There’re a lot of reviews about this book being an epic, and the 20th century answer to War and Peace. But for me it was just an incredibly engaging story, never have I felt this with Tolstoy’s work.<br>This novel is panoramic in scope, Grossman looks very wide, tries to give us the biggest slice of life he can. <br><br>It is about war and about civilians trying to survive in nazi concentration camps, GULAG, in evacuation, under occupation, on the battlefront. Stakes couldn’t be higher, risks are immense. But people continue with their lives, they fall in love and out of love. They suffer and persevere. And this is all in the novel that Grossman didn't have a chance to edit. <br><br>And we had so many tender scenes and scenes that rip your heart out. We have a letter from Shtrum’s mother from the jewish ghetto before her death. Adorable young love of Katya and Sergey in the middle of the battle. Sofia and little David's heart wrenching scene of arriving at Auschwitz. Young Vera stays in Stalingrad in the middle of the battle to be closer to her husband and gives birth to their child, while her husband dies. And a lot more.<br>I thought at first this work was not very psychological, but we have a great exploration of a tragedy of Viktor Shtrum. His desperation, elation and ultimate weakness and complete surrender to the state. <br><br>This is not a book I wanted to rush through, I was savoring it for a month. <br>The story is deeply patriotic and disheartened. It ends in sadness, the victory is reachable and Stalin’s state machine of repressions is starting already. Grossman knows what's coming. <br><br><blockquote>Everyone was asleep – the strong and the weak, the brave and the timid, the happy and the unhappy. This was a last parting, in an empty and abandoned house, with the dead who had now left it for ever. Somehow you could sense spring more vividly in this cool forest than on the sunlit plain. And there was a deeper sadness in this silence than in the silence of autumn. In it you could hear both a lament for the dead and the furious joy of life itself. It was still cold and dark, but soon the doors and shutters would be flung open. Soon the house would be filled with the tears and laughter of children, with the hurried steps of a loved woman and the measured gait of the master of the house. <br>They stood there, holding their bags, in silence.</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="17107451110685692859" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

